body:
I took a look at the current patch.  I saw a synchronization problem, I will comment about that on the patch.   I am still thinking this over, but I am thinking of a slightly different model.  I am not sure about the behavior of one thread closing the connection while another is using.  Below is some code to try to outline what I am thinking.  I am thinking of checking if the oracle changed _after_ making an RPC call to the oracle.   

``` java
class OracleClient {

  //leader id format : <ip>:<port>:<uuid>
  private String currentLeaderID;

  class TimestampRetriever{
     doWork(){

          .
          .
          .

        // code to get a block of timestamps...
        while(true){

         syncronized(this){
             //this could change while running... grab it here and check 
             //at the end this code is not needed if this is the only thread 
             //the changes the connection
             myConnectedLeaderID = connectedLeader
             myClient = client
         }

          time = myClient.getTimestamps(...);

          //check for leader change AFTER talking to oracle... it posible 
          //when the request was sent the connection was to a valid 
          //oracle... but maybe  that oracle paused and processed our 
          //request after losing leadership
          if(!myConnectedLeaderID.equals(getCurrentLeaderID()){
            reconnect();
            continue;
          }
          break;
        }

         .
         . 
         .
     }

  //code to connect to oracle server... this method synced because want to 
  //set client and connectorLeaderID together
  synchronized connect(){
     tmpID = leaderSelector.getLeader().getID();
     //make thrift connection

     //ensure oracle is uuid we expect.. .this ensures oracle server is one we 
     //expect
     if(!client.checkID(getUUID(tmpID))){
        throw;
     }

     //only set this after successful connection
     connectorLeaderID = tmpID;

  }

  public void childEvent( ){
     if (pathChildrenCacheEvent.getType().toString().startsWith("CHILD")) {
       synchronized (this){
         //does the call to getLeader() reach out an read from zookeeper?  or does 
         //it read from cached data?
         currentLeaderID = leaderSelector.getLeader();
       }
     }
  }

  synchronized String getCurrentLeaderID()){
     //this is obtained in an eventually consistent manner... 
     //I am stilling thinking if instead it should reach out and read 
     //from ZK... could possibly do this at least every 
     //zkSessionTimeout/2
     return currentLeaderID;
  }
}
```
